7367848431768964398.voice_to_text: I just wanted to make a quick follow-up video to say I officially graduated today as valedictorian of my college class! Now that I've officially graduated, I wanted to share my Persona 5 inspired valedictorian speech. Here it goes: I'm honoured to have been chosen as a valedictorian of this year's graduating class. My name is Raven and I am a Secondary Education and English major with double minors in Art and Writing. In true English major fashion, on my graduation cap I've written a quote from one of my favourite characters of all time, “I will carve my own path for myself.” We've all likely encountered individuals who entrust others with their destinies to such an extent that they unconsciously relinquish some of their freedoms in the process. Perhaps, we've been in that position ourselves, seeking external guidance to fulfill others’ ideas of happiness in the hope that that happiness will become our own. However, genuine growth and happiness emerge from following our inner compass and forging paths aligned with our deepest aspirations. I am the eldest daughter of immigrants. I am a first generation college student. I am an English major, even though English is not my first language. Despite encountering skepticism about my potential for success, I have remained steadfast in my self-belief and identity. Of course, there are times when relying on and trusting others is essential. I could not have overcome the numerous linguistic and societal barriers I faced because of my background alone. However, the pivotal decisions, born of my free will, forged a path I proudly tread alongside you all as fellow graduates. Trust is a precious gift—to ourselves as much as others. Embracing challenges fosters growth, yet surrendering crucial decisions to external forces only hinders true happiness and self-pride. “What's a life worth in a reality that was cooked up just to satisfy someone else?” “I say ‘none.’” Your happiness and development rest solely in your hands. Carve your own path for yourself, drawing upon the skills and knowledge that have been infused in our education by our founders to shape a narrative you can be proud of. To anyone graduating this season, congratulations class of 2024!

7367032745865809198.voice_to_text: Endeavor so doesn't get a redemption arc. Like, he just doesn't deserve one. Oh, god. Well, then it's a good thing that the point of his character is that he is not getting redemption. Yes, to us it is a redemption arc. Because we in our world see our character goes from bad to good. They have a redemption arc. But what endeavor is getting is not redemption. It. It is atonement. And he acknowledges this within the sea, where Koshi makes it very clear. Endeavor knows he cannot be forgiven. He knows the acts he has done are beyond forgiveness. And the point of Endeavor's character is not at all to be forgiven. Cause again, it is acknowledged within the series that he can't be forgiven. He is beyond forgiveness. But the point of his character is to show atonement. To show that someone who has done something terrible can continue to live on. And even if they're not forgiven, they can seek to be better and do better. Not to get forgiveness, but to make up for the past. To try to atone for their sins. And even if they're not forgiven, at least they're doing something to be better. And that's the point of Endeavor's character. That's why Horikoshi hasn't killed him off. Horikoshi has had plenty of opportunities where he could have killed him off, but he's still kicking. Because the point of his character is to live and to see the future and to help The future heroes be better. To make sure that there's never another endeavor. That's the point of this character. Not to be forgiven, but to atone and to help make the future better.

It getting a anime remake might be a little bit too much and might burn out the audience for one piece. I disagree with this take because of one very specific reason. All of these sources for one piece are targeting a relatively different demographic. You've got people who are die hard anime fans. They've been watching the one piece anime since 1999, and they are watching it every single week. You also have people who are manga fans who prefer to consume this kind of content in a manga format. And on top of that, the live action just brought in a massive demographic that has been very averse to starting the anime or the manga because of how long they are. All of these formats do a fantastic job of telling this amazing story that we love to an audience that wouldn't normally consume it otherwise. I would say the number one barrier to get anybody into the one piece anime or manga is because it's too long and the pacing is rough. And for current anime and manga readers, it's way off the base for what they're used to consuming. So I think getting a remake gives one piece another amazing chance to get deep into the hearts of the newer anime and Manga fan base so do I think this is gonna cause burnout? No, another side of this is one piece fans or one piece fans. They're gonna consume it in all possible facets. Once I catch up on the one piece anime, I'm sure I'm gonna be jumping over the manga to consume more content. And I'm gonna watch season 2 of the live action the moment it drops cause I'm super excited about that too because again, I love one piece. And finally when they do remake the anime, I'm gonna be watching that as well. I'm hyped for it. I do not think this is gonna cause fatigue because I think the people who like one piece in their certain forms will continue consuming it that way. 7374523118267698474.voice_to_text: Why do so many people want the villains to win in Jujutsu Kaisen? Because outside of the fact that this would be a subversion of expectations, what good would the writing do if sukuna won? What it would mean for the story is that sukuna was right the entire time. Throwing everything away for the sake of power is the correct way to do things in the world of jujutsu society. That being alone is better than being surrounded by those you love. And I'm not saying that you can't have a different ideological perspective, but why would that be the perspective that you guys would want to win in the end? There's a reason that the power of friendship is such a trope, not just in shonen, but just in media in general. Because in real life, there's no part of oh yeah, let me just be alone always and forever. That sounds like an actually legitimately good idea, and even logically from any kind of media. Whenever you're battling somebody, there's literally strength in numbers. That's a saying for a reason. So despite everything, I don't think Tsuka is gonna win in the end. 7371410569221492010.voice_to_text: Something that seems to confuse a lot of people is the idea that dodging a light speed attack does not make you light speed. Let me break down why that is with this diagram right here. Let's say you got Person A and Person B. Person B decides to fire a laser beam at Person A. Person A responds by moving their head out of the way, allowing the laser beam to just pass right by them. This laser beam is moving at light speed. However, that person's head was not moving at light speed. Hopefully this makes it, like, easier to understand. But let's say that the laser beam leaves the person's hand and travels 10 feet to get to their opponent, and the person that moved their head out of the side moved their head 6 inches. It took the same amount of time for this laser beam to move 10 feet as it did for this person's head to move 6 inches. Since this covered less distance in the same amount of time, this movement is not relative, speed wise, to the movement of that laser beam. Now, this is also assuming that they started moving their head when the laser was fired, but that's not really how our brains work. Good analogue for this is pitchers and batters in baseball. On average, it takes less than half a second for a fastball to leave the pitcher's hand and make it to home plate. And yet the Average reaction time in the MLB is point seven, five or three quarters of a second. The way that they're still able to hit these fastballs even though their reaction time isn't fast enough to do so is by predicting where the ball is going to go and starting to swing the bat before the pitcher even throws the ball. In the context of a fight, this would be someone looking at the opponent's weapon and determining where it's aiming and preemptively moving out of the path of that projectile. How would you take a situation like this and make it a light speed feat? Well, let's take the same situation. You have two people 10 feet apart. One of them is charging up a laser beam. Person A is being attacked. Person B is charging laser beam. So Person B fires their laser. Now, in this situation, in the time that it takes that laser to travel the 10 feet to the target, that target is able to move 10 feet out of the way. Because they moved 10 feet in the same amount of time that it took that laser beam to travel 10 feet. That would make this feet light speed, because the person is actually moving at the same speed as that laser beam.

7369062678939176235.voice_to_text: X defiant is about to be a top three FPS game, all thanks to a major decision that players have been begging to see from call of duty. The peak call of duty games and X defiant actually have a lot of things in common, one of them being the brains behind the operation, Mark Rubin, who worked for Activision as the executive producer during the Modern Warfare series. But more importantly, he understands better than anyone that skill based matchmaking has played a huge factor in a call of duty struggles. So today the team released a statement confirming there will be no skill based matchmaking in the casual playlist for X Defiance. The statement continues on saying skill based matchmaking means every casual game is repetitive, constantly repeating matches that are just as stressful as ranked. We believe casual playlist should be fun and varied, similar to how prime call of duty was. X defiant will find matches in order of these priorities latency avoided, players, party size, region, input device, and then platform. Once in the lobby. Teams will still be balanced though. 7341040159565106462.voice_to_text: To a child who isn't loved properly, the answer one might expect is that they start to hate the person who doesn't give them the love they need. But far from it, the reality is that the child becomes filled with shame, a sense that it's profoundly unworthy, dirty, soiled, sinful, ugly, embarrassing. The child is unable to redirect the blame outwards. It doesn't ask what's wrong with my parents for not loving me adequately? It simply wonders in a fullon way what have I done wrong in order to have ended up on the receiving end of my parents disapproval? The child prefers to attack itself for being bad than to confront a yet more awful possibility that it's entirely dependent for its well being on inadequate and unkind parental figures. The child searches for explanations for the lack of love it has to endure and comes up with all the wrong answers. It concludes I've not been impressive enough, and therefore it undertakes enormous efforts to prove to itself and outsiders that it does nevertheless deserve to exist. At school, this kind of child might try seven times as hard as any other to show that it's clever and good. Or else a child may go down an anti social route and graffiti the nearby underpass as a desperate way of giving out would form to a feeling of badness it's tortured by inside. There is so sadly no way out from the burden of shame available either By trying to be extremely good or extremely bad, the only solution is to work against the grain of forgetting, in order to perceive for the first time an awful possibility that one could never perceive as a child, that one has done nothing wrong at all, that wrong was done to one
